Note:
LLVM IR Lexer - Tokenizes LLVM Intermediate Representation

This file provides lexical analysis for LLVM IR, the typed assembly language
used by the LLVM compiler infrastructure. LLVM IR is in SSA (Static Single
Assignment) form with a comprehensive type system and instruction set.

LLVM IR Structure:
- Module-level declarations (globals, functions, types)
- Function definitions with basic blocks
- SSA form with virtual registers
- Typed instructions and operands
- Metadata and attributes

Token Types:
- Keywords (define, declare, ret, br, load, store, call, etc.)
- Types (i1, i8, i32, i64, float, double, void, ptr, etc.)
- Identifiers (@global, %local, %0, %1)
- Literals (integers, floats, strings, null, true, false)
- Operators and delimiters (=, *, x, {, }, [, ], <, >, (, ), ,, :)
- Attributes (signext, zeroext, noalias, nonnull, align)
- Metadata (!0, !1, !dbg)

Dependencies:
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Types
Note: ============================================================================

Constant TOKEN_KEYWORD as Integer is 1
Constant TOKEN_TYPE as Integer is 2
Constant TOKEN_GLOBAL_ID as Integer is 3
Constant TOKEN_LOCAL_ID as Integer is 4
Constant TOKEN_NUMBER as Integer is 5
Constant TOKEN_LABEL as Integer is 6
Constant TOKEN_STRING as Integer is 7
Constant TOKEN_METADATA as Integer is 8
Constant TOKEN_EQUALS as Integer is 9
Constant TOKEN_STAR as Integer is 10
Constant TOKEN_LPAREN as Integer is 11
Constant TOKEN_RPAREN as Integer is 12
Constant TOKEN_LBRACE as Integer is 13
Constant TOKEN_RBRACE as Integer is 14
Constant TOKEN_LBRACKET as Integer is 15
Constant TOKEN_RBRACKET as Integer is 16
Constant TOKEN_LANGLE as Integer is 17
Constant TOKEN_RANGLE as Integer is 18
Constant TOKEN_COMMA as Integer is 19
Constant TOKEN_COLON as Integer is 20
Constant TOKEN_X as Integer is 21
Constant TOKEN_TO as Integer is 22
Constant TOKEN_EOF as Integer is 23
Constant TOKEN_ERROR as Integer is 24

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
LLVM IR token record. Stores lexeme as pointer+length (rather than
heap-allocated string) so the lexer can carve tokens out of the
source buffer in-place without per-token allocations - critical for
LLVM IR files which can be hundreds of thousands of tokens.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Five-field record: token_type (TOKEN_* constant), lexeme (pointer
into the source buffer), lexeme_length (byte count), line, column.
@End Implementation
Type called "LLVMIRToken":
    token_type as Integer      Note: Token type constant
    lexeme as Integer          Note: Pointer to lexeme string
    lexeme_length as Integer   Note: Length of lexeme
    line as Integer            Note: Line number
    column as Integer          Note: Column number
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer State
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lexer state tracking both the current cursor (position/line/column)
and the "start" anchor for the in-progress token (start_*). The
anchor approach lets the lexer mark the beginning of a token before
walking, then build the token record with the exact starting
position once the token end is determined.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Eight-field record: source (pointer), source_length, position (byte
offset), line, column (current cursor), start_position, start_line,
start_column (token-start anchor). The anchor fields are updated by
the caller via make_token at the start of each token-scan sequence.
@End Implementation
Type called "LLVMIRLexer":
    source as Integer          Note: Source code pointer
    source_length as Integer   Note: Source code length
    position as Integer        Note: Current position in source
    line as Integer            Note: Current line number
    column as Integer          Note: Current column number
    start_position as Integer  Note: Start position of current token
    start_line as Integer      Note: Start line of current token
    start_column as Integer    Note: Start column of current token
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates and initialises a fresh LLVMIRLexer at the source start.
Both current cursor and start anchor begin at position 0, line 1,
column 1 - the typical zero state for a not-yet-started lex.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls string_length on source. Allocates 64 bytes (8 i64 slots).
Returns 0 on failure. Writes: source @0, source_length @8,
position @16 = 0, line @24 = 1, column @32 = 1, start_position @40
= 0, start_line @48 = 1, start_column @56 = 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_llvmir_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let source_length be proc string_length from StringCore with source

    Let lexer_size be 64  Note: LLVMIRLexer: 8 fields × 8 bytes
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, source_length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 0   Note: position = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1   Note: line = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1   Note: column = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 0   Note: start_position = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, 1   Note: start_line = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, 1   Note: start_column = 1

    Return lexer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Examination
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Non-destructive read of the current byte. All scan loops use this
to decide whether to consume or stop, then call advance_char to
actually consume. Splitting peek and advance lets the lexer take
the same byte through multiple classification paths without
duplicating reads.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position @16 and source_length @8. If position >=
source_length, returns 0 as an EOF sentinel (LLVM IR cannot
contain a NUL byte outside of string literals, so 0 is safe as a
sentinel here). Otherwise reads source @0 and returns the byte at
source[position] via memory_get_byte.
@End Implementation
Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current character without advancing

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
One-byte lookahead. Used by next_token to decide whether '-' starts
a negative number (followed by a digit) versus a stray dash. Single
byte of lookahead is sufficient for the LLVM IR grammar handled
here - no scanner currently needs deeper peeking.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Same shape as peek_char but uses position + 1. EOF guard compares
position + 1 against source_length (so the last byte of the source
returns 0 from peek_next_char while peek_char still yields the
real byte). Returns the byte at source[position + 1].
@End Implementation
Process called "peek_next_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at next character without advancing

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position plus 1 is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position plus 1

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-byte step + position/line/column bookkeeping. Returns the
byte that was AT the position before stepping (consistent with the
"read then advance" model used by all scan_* loops). Newlines reset
column to 1 and bump line - critical for accurate diagnostics later.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls peek_char to capture the current byte. Increments position
@16 by 1 and column @32 by 1. If the captured byte is LF (10),
increments line @24 by 1 and overwrites column back to 1. CR is
not specifically handled - in CRLF, the LF that follows resets
column correctly, and in bare-CR sources column tracking is off
by one which we accept as an extremely rare LLVM IR producer.
@End Implementation
Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance position and return current character

    Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, column plus 1

    Note: Handle newlines
    If char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1  Note: column = 1
    End If

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII letter classifier. LLVM IR identifiers are ASCII-only (the
spec does not allow Unicode in identifier syntax) so we only need
A-Z and a-z ranges. We deliberately don't use a library function -
this is called once per byte during lexing and inlining the range
check keeps the hot path branch-predictable.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two range checks: 65..90 ('A'..'Z') and 97..122 ('a'..'z'). Each
range is implemented as nested ifs to permit early return on the
first match. Returns 0 if neither range matches.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic

    If char is greater than or equal to 65:  Note: 'A'
        If char is less than or equal to 90:  Note: 'Z'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to 97:  Note: 'a'
        If char is less than or equal to 122:  Note: 'z'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII decimal-digit classifier. Used in number scanning, integer-
type detection (i<N>), and the alnum predicate. Pure range check
on byte values 48..57 - no locale dependency.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two-level if: char >= 48 ('0') AND char <= 57 ('9') -> return 1,
else return 0. Nested rather than combined to mirror is_alpha's
structure.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is numeric

    If char is greater than or equal to 48:  Note: '0'
        If char is less than or equal to 57:  Note: '9'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Disjunction of is_alpha and is_digit. Used by identifier-shaped
scans (after the first character) where LLVM IR allows letters and
digits intermixed. Implemented as two sequential helper calls
rather than inlining the range checks to keep the rule centralised.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls is_alpha, returns 1 if it returns 1. Otherwise calls
is_digit, returns 1 if it returns 1. Returns 0 if neither matches.
Underscore (95) and dot (46) are intentionally NOT considered
alnum here - they are handled by separate branches at each call
site because their permission varies by token kind.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_alnum" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphanumeric

    Let alpha be proc is_alpha with char
    If alpha is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let digit be proc is_digit with char
    If digit is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII whitespace classifier. LLVM IR uses the standard four
whitespace bytes (space, tab, LF, CR). We do NOT treat vertical tab
or form-feed as whitespace - they would be lexical errors in well-
formed LLVM IR and treating them as whitespace would silently mask
malformed inputs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 for 32 (space), 9 (TAB), 10 (LF), 13 (CR); 0 otherwise.
Structured as four sequential ifs rather than a single boolean
expression to match the rest of the lexer's style and ensure each
branch is a simple terminal Return.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_whitespace" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is whitespace

    If char is equal to 32:  Note: space
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 9:  Note: tab
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 13:  Note: carriage return
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Materialises an LLVMIRToken from the lexer's current start_*
anchor and current position. The token's lexeme is an OWNED,
NUL-terminated byte copy of the source slice (source + start_position,
length bytes). A copy — rather than a slice pointer into the source
buffer — is required because downstream string comparison and
length routines (string_equals, string_length, set_node_name)
treat the lexeme as a C string and would over-read past the token
boundary on a bare slice that is not NUL-terminated.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 40 bytes (5 i64 fields) for the token record. Computes
length = current_pos - start_pos. Allocates length+1 bytes for the
owned lexeme, copies the source slice into it via memory_copy, and
writes a NUL terminator at index length. Writes token_type @0,
owned-lexeme pointer @8, length @16, start_line @24, start_column
@32. Returns the token pointer. If either allocation fails the
partial token is freed and 0 is returned so the caller treats it
as a fatal lexer error.
@End Implementation
Process called "make_token" takes lexer as Integer, token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create token from current lexeme

    Let token_size be 40  Note: LLVMIRToken: 5 fields × 8 bytes
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be current_pos minus start_pos

    Let start_line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48
    Let start_column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56

    Note: Allocate an owned, NUL-terminated copy of the lexeme slice
    Let lexeme be proc allocate from Layout with length plus 1

    If lexeme is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with token
        Return 0
    End If

    Let slice_start be source plus start_pos
    proc memory_copy from Layout with lexeme, slice_start, length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with lexeme, length, 0

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, lexeme
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, start_line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 32, start_column

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Builds a TOKEN_ERROR record carrying a static C-string message
(passed as a pointer constant from the caller). Reuses the same
40-byte token layout as make_token so consumers can use a single
free path regardless of token kind.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a token, sets token_type = TOKEN_ERROR, places the
message pointer in the lexeme slot (consumers treat the lexeme as
a null-terminated C string in this case), sets lexeme_length = 0
(the message length is implied by the C string), and copies the
CURRENT line/column (not start anchor) so the error points to
where the lexer was when it gave up.
@End Implementation
Process called "make_error_token" takes lexer as Integer, message as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create error token

    Let token_size be 40  Note: LLVMIRToken: 5 fields × 8 bytes
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, TOKEN_ERROR
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 32, column

    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Whitespace and Comments
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Consumes the inter-token noise in LLVM IR: ASCII whitespace and
semicolon-introduced line comments. Skipping is folded into one
function so the main scanner does not have to alternate between
whitespace and comment loops itself.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Outer infinite loop. On EOF returns 1. On whitespace, advances and
continues. On ';' (59), enters an inner loop that advances until
either newline or EOF and then continues the outer loop (so a
comment ending in a newline lets the outer loop also strip any
whitespace that follows). On any other character, returns 1 to
hand control back to next_token.
@End Implementation
Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip whitespace and comments

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:
            Return 1  Note: EOF
        End If

        Let is_ws be proc is_whitespace with char

        If is_ws is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Note: Check for comment
            If char is equal to 59:  Note: semicolon (;)
                Note: Line comment until newline
                While 1 is equal to 1:
                    Let c be proc peek_char with lexer

                    If c is equal to 0:
                        Return 1  Note: EOF
                    End If

                    If c is equal to 10:  Note: newline
                        Break
                    End If

                    proc advance_char with lexer
                End While
            Otherwise:
                Return 1  Note: Not whitespace or comment
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Keyword and Type Recognition
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Length-prefixed byte-equality check. Both arguments are pointer +
length so the comparison is exact and does not depend on null
termination - important because the lexeme is a slice into the
source buffer with no terminator after it.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Early-out length mismatch first (the cheapest possible reject).
Then walk index 0..length comparing memory_get_byte on each side,
returning 0 immediately on the first mismatch. This makes prefix-
mismatches the fast common case during keyword lookup.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_keyword" takes lexeme as Integer, length as Integer, keyword as Integer, keyword_length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if lexeme matches keyword

    If length is not equal to keyword_length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let index be 0

    While index is less than length:
        Let c1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with lexeme, index
        Let c2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with keyword, index

        If c1 is not equal to c2:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recognises LLVM IR keywords. Organised by lexeme length first to
prune the search space - for any given identifier we only compare
against keywords of the same length. This is a hot path during
lexing (every identifier-shaped token triggers it), so the
length-bucket structure is a deliberate constant-factor win.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Length-2 bucket: "to", "br". Length-3: ret/add/sub/mul/and/xor/shl.
Length-4: call/load/sdiv/udiv/srem/urem/ashr/lshr/icmp/fcmp/fadd/
fsub/fmul/fdiv/frem/null/true/type/void. Length-5: store/false/
align/float. Length-6: alloca/define/switch/double/global.
Length-7: declare/signext/zeroext/noalias/nonnull. Length-8:
constant. Length-14: getelementptr. Returns 1 on match, 0 otherwise.
Each check is a check_keyword call with the length already proven
equal so the inner loop just compares bytes.
@End Implementation
@Performance_Hints:
This is called for every identifier token. The length-bucketing
saves dispatching all ~40 string comparisons per identifier - in
the common case (e.g. a 4-char identifier), only the length-4
bucket is examined.
@End Performance_Hints
Process called "is_llvm_keyword" takes lexeme as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if identifier is LLVM IR keyword

    @Reasoning:
    LLVM IR has many keywords for instructions, declarations, and attributes.
    We check common keywords by length for efficiency.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Length 2
    If length is equal to 2:
        Let matches be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "to", 2
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "br", 2
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Length 3
    If length is equal to 3:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "ret", 3
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "add", 3
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "sub", 3
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "mul", 3
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "and", 3
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "xor", 3
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "shl", 3
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Length 4
    If length is equal to 4:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "call", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "load", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "sdiv", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "udiv", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "srem", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "urem", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "ashr", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "lshr", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "icmp", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "fcmp", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "fadd", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "fsub", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "fmul", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "fdiv", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "frem", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "null", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "true", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "type", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "void", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Length 5
    If length is equal to 5:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "store", 5
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "false", 5
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "align", 5
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "float", 5
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Length 6
    If length is equal to 6:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "alloca", 6
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "define", 6
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "switch", 6
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "double", 6
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "global", 6
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Length 7
    If length is equal to 7:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "declare", 7
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "signext", 7
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "zeroext", 7
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "noalias", 7
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "nonnull", 7
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Length 8
    If length is equal to 8:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "constant", 8
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Length 14
    If length is equal to 14:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "getelementptr", 14
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Distinguishes LLVM IR type spellings from generic identifiers. The
hardest case is integer types: LLVM uses 'i<N>' for any bit-width
(i1, i8, i16, i32, i64, i128, also non-standard widths like i7) so
a single keyword check cannot work - we must recognise the 'i'
prefix followed by digits algorithmically.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
First branch: if lexeme[0] == 'i' (105) and the remaining bytes are
all digits, classify as integer type. Then exact matches: "ptr",
"void", "float", "double". Other LLVM type spellings (half, fp128,
x86_fp80, label, token, metadata, opaque) are not in this short
list - they fall through to identifier classification and are
resolved by the parser using context. This keeps the lexer hot path
small for the four most common scalar types.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_llvm_type" takes lexeme as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if identifier is LLVM IR type

    Note: Integer types (i1, i8, i16, i32, i64, i128)
    If length is greater than or equal to 2:
        Let first_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with lexeme, 0

        If first_char is equal to 105:  Note: 'i'
            Let all_digits be 1
            Let index be 1

            While index is less than length:
                Let c be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with lexeme, index
                Let is_d be proc is_digit with c

                If is_d is equal to 0:
                    Set all_digits to 0
                    Break
                End If

                Set index to index plus 1
            End While

            If all_digits is equal to 1:
                Return 1  Note: Integer type like i32
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check specific types
    If length is equal to 3:
        Let matches be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "ptr", 3
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 4:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "void", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 5:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "float", 5
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 6:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "double", 6
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Scanners
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans an identifier-shaped lexeme then classifies it. LLVM IR
identifiers permit alphanumerics, underscores, and dots (e.g.
'br.cond.true'). The result is classified as TOKEN_KEYWORD,
TOKEN_TYPE, or generic identifier (also reported as TOKEN_KEYWORD
in this lexer - downstream layers disambiguate by content).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops accepting [A-Za-z0-9_.]. Then computes the lexeme span
(source + start_position, current - start) and consults
is_llvm_keyword and is_llvm_type. is_llvm_keyword takes precedence
over is_llvm_type because the keyword table is a superset for any
overlapping spellings. Unclassified identifiers fall through as
TOKEN_KEYWORD - this is intentional and parser layers decide
whether each one is a label, attribute name, etc.
@End Implementation
Process called "scan_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan identifier or keyword

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let is_an be proc is_alnum with char

        If is_an is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Note: Allow underscores and dots in identifiers
            If char is equal to 95:  Note: underscore
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                If char is equal to 46:  Note: dot
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Determine if keyword or type
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be current_pos minus start_pos
    Let lexeme be source plus start_pos

    Let is_kw be proc is_llvm_keyword with lexeme, length

    If is_kw is equal to 1:
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_KEYWORD
    End If

    Let is_ty be proc is_llvm_type with lexeme, length

    If is_ty is equal to 1:
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_TYPE
    End If

    Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_KEYWORD  Note: Treat as keyword/identifier
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans an LLVM IR numeric literal. LLVM IR numbers can be integer
constants (42, -7), floating-point (3.14, 1.0e-5), or hex
floating-point. The lexer is liberal here - it collects any
plausible numeric character run and lets the parser validate the
actual numeric form against the operand's expected type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops while peek_char yields a digit, '.', 'e', '-', or '+'. Note
the dispatcher handles the leading sign separately for negatives;
the in-loop '-'/'+' acceptance is for exponent signs (e.g. 1.5e-3).
Returns TOKEN_NUMBER with the lexeme covering the entire numeric
run. Does not validate well-formedness - that is the parser's job.
@End Implementation
Process called "scan_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan numeric literal

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let is_d be proc is_digit with char

        If is_d is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Note: Allow dots for floats, 'e' for scientific notation, '-' for negative
            If char is equal to 46:  Note: dot
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                If char is equal to 101:  Note: 'e'
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    If char is equal to 45:  Note: minus
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                    Otherwise:
                        If char is equal to 43:  Note: plus
                            proc advance_char with lexer
                        Otherwise:
                            Break
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_NUMBER
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans an LLVM IR double-quoted string literal. LLVM IR uses these
for things like global C-string constants (c"...") and metadata
strings. Backslash escapes are PASSED THROUGH unchanged - the
parser/decoder layer handles \xx hex escapes; the lexer only needs
to skip the escaped byte so it isn't mistaken for a closing quote.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the opening quote then loops byte-by-byte until a closing
'"' is found. On EOF mid-string, returns error token "Unterminated
string". On backslash (92), advances past the backslash AND the
next byte (guarding against EOF on the escape character). The
final token's lexeme range covers the entire span including both
quote characters.
@End Implementation
Process called "scan_string" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan string literal

    proc advance_char with lexer  Note: Opening quote

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:
            Return proc make_error_token with lexer, "Unterminated string"
        End If

        If char is equal to 34:  Note: closing quote
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Break
        End If

        Note: Handle escape sequences
        If char is equal to 92:  Note: backslash
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Let next_char be proc peek_char with lexer

            If next_char is not equal to 0:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
        Otherwise:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
    End While

    Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_STRING
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Scanner
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Main token-dispatch entry point. Calls skip_whitespace (which also
strips ; line comments) and then snapshots position/line/column
into the start_* anchor fields BEFORE reading the first byte - this
is what makes make_token report the correct token-start location
even though the cursor walks forward during scan_identifier/etc.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dispatch order: alpha -> scan_identifier, '@' -> global id,
'%' -> local id, '!' -> metadata, digit -> scan_number, '-' followed
by digit -> negative scan_number, '"' -> scan_string, else single-
char operators. Identifier-class tokens (@, %, !) accept alnum plus
underscore and dot in subsequent positions (matches LLVM's identifier
grammar). EOF returns TOKEN_EOF; unknown byte returns error token.
@End Implementation
Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan next token from source

    proc skip_whitespace with lexer

    Note: Update token start position
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, position
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, column

    Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

    If char is equal to 0:
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_EOF
    End If

    Note: Check for identifiers
    Let is_a be proc is_alpha with char

    If is_a is equal to 1:
        Return proc scan_identifier with lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for global identifier (@name)
    If char is equal to 64:  Note: @
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Let next_char be proc peek_char with lexer

        Note: Must be followed by alphanumeric or number
        Let is_an be proc is_alnum with next_char

        If is_an is equal to 1:
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let c be proc peek_char with lexer
                Let is_an2 be proc is_alnum with c

                If is_an2 is equal to 1:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    If c is equal to 95:  Note: underscore
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                    Otherwise:
                        If c is equal to 46:  Note: dot
                            proc advance_char with lexer
                        Otherwise:
                            Break
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End While

            Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_GLOBAL_ID
        End If

        Return proc make_error_token with lexer, "Invalid global identifier"
    End If

    Note: Check for local identifier (%name or %0)
    If char is equal to 37:  Note: %
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set next_char to proc peek_char with lexer

        Note: Must be followed by alphanumeric
        Set is_an to proc is_alnum with next_char

        If is_an is equal to 1:
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Set c to proc peek_char with lexer
                Set is_an2 to proc is_alnum with c

                If is_an2 is equal to 1:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    If c is equal to 95:  Note: underscore
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                    Otherwise:
                        If c is equal to 46:  Note: dot
                            proc advance_char with lexer
                        Otherwise:
                            Break
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End While

            Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_LOCAL_ID
        End If

        Return proc make_error_token with lexer, "Invalid local identifier"
    End If

    Note: Check for metadata (!0, !dbg)
    If char is equal to 33:  Note: !
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set next_char to proc peek_char with lexer

        Note: Can be followed by number or identifier
        Set is_an to proc is_alnum with next_char

        If is_an is equal to 1:
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Set c to proc peek_char with lexer
                Set is_an2 to proc is_alnum with c

                If is_an2 is equal to 1:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End While

            Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_METADATA
        End If

        Return proc make_error_token with lexer, "Invalid metadata"
    End If

    Note: Check for numbers
    Let is_d be proc is_digit with char

    If is_d is equal to 1:
        Return proc scan_number with lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for negative numbers
    If char is equal to 45:  Note: minus
        Set next_char to proc peek_next_char with lexer
        Let is_d2 be proc is_digit with next_char

        If is_d2 is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc scan_number with lexer
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for strings
    If char is equal to 34:  Note: double quote
        Return proc scan_string with lexer
    End If

    Note: Single character tokens
    proc advance_char with lexer

    If char is equal to 61:  Note: =
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_EQUALS
    End If

    If char is equal to 42:  Note: *
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_STAR
    End If

    If char is equal to 40:  Note: (
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_LPAREN
    End If

    If char is equal to 41:  Note: )
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_RPAREN
    End If

    If char is equal to 123:  Note: {
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_LBRACE
    End If

    If char is equal to 125:  Note: }
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_RBRACE
    End If

    If char is equal to 91:  Note: [
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_LBRACKET
    End If

    If char is equal to 93:  Note: ]
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_RBRACKET
    End If

    If char is equal to 60:  Note: <
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_LANGLE
    End If

    If char is equal to 62:  Note: >
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_RANGLE
    End If

    If char is equal to 44:  Note: ,
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_COMMA
    End If

    If char is equal to 58:  Note: :
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_COLON
    End If

    If char is equal to 120:  Note: x
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_X
    End If

    Return proc make_error_token with lexer, "Unexpected character"
End Process
